The basic rule is that the board of directors of a company is in charge of =
the company, and when they are faced with a decision, the directors are sup=
posed to make the choice that they believe is best for the company and all =
of its shareholders. The shareholders don=E2=80=99t make the decision; the =
board does.
  [1]
=C2=A0
Now, the directors are elected by the shareholders, and when the company ha=
s a controlling shareholder, the idea that the directors are in charge can =
feel somewhat absurd. The controlling shareholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0say, a fou=
nder and chief executive officer who owns 60% of the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0c=
an come into the boardroom and say =E2=80=9CI want you to sell all of the c=
ompany=E2=80=99s assets to me for $1,=E2=80=9D and the directors will say =
=E2=80=9Cno, in our independent judgment that=E2=80=99s a bad idea,=E2=80=
=9D and the founder/CEO/shareholder will say =E2=80=9Cokay you=E2=80=99re f=
ired,=E2=80=9D and she will replace them with more pliable directors. And s=
he can do that, because she has the votes.
  [2]
=C2=A0But still: The directors are supposed to exercise their independent j=
udgment and do what is in the company=E2=80=99s best interests, and if they=
 conclude that the founder/CEO=E2=80=99s plan is bad, they have to say no a=
nd get fired. They can=E2=80=99t just say =E2=80=9Cwell, ultimately she con=
trols the company, so we have to do what she asks.=E2=80=9D Exercising inde=
pendent judgment is their job.
I cannot promise that every board of directors of every company sees things=
 this way =E2=80=94=C2=A0I think some directors of private startups see the=
ir job as =E2=80=9Cadvise and empower the founder/CEO=E2=80=9D rather than =
=E2=80=9Cexercise independent judgment=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the cour=
ts in Delaware, where most US public companies are incorporated, definitely=
 see things this way.
  [3]
=C2=A0So we   talked recently=C2=A0about a Delaware court decision overturn=
ing Elon Musk=E2=80=99s pay package at Tesla Inc. The basic theory there wa=
s that Musk is Tesla=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder (even though he owns=
 a minority of the stock), and that the board did not exercise sufficient i=
ndependent judgment in deciding what to pay him: He asked for a pay package=
 and they deferred to what he wanted. Not okay, said the judge; the board h=
as a duty to make its own independent determination of what he should be pa=
id.
Ken Moelis is the founder, chief executive officer and chairman of the boar=
d of directors of Moelis & Co., the investment bank. In 2014, Moelis & Co. =
went public, and over time Ken Moelis sold some of his stock. He now owns a=
bout 6.5% of the stock, but he has some supervoting shares, which give him =
about 40.4% of the voting power of the stock.
  [4]
=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s not a majority, but it=E2=80=99s a lot more than Elon =
Musk owns of Tesla:=C2=A0Ken Moelis is not necessarily the controlling shar=
eholder of Moelis & Co., but he=E2=80=99s at least pretty close.
Beyond his voting stake, though, Ken Moelis has some extra control over his=
 company. Specifically there is a  Stockholders Agreement=C2=A0that gives K=
en Moelis some rights to control the company:
=09He gets to designate a majority of the board of directors: He can name h=
is candidates, and the company=E2=80=99s board is obligated to nominate the=
m, recommend that stockholders vote for them, and try to get them elected.
  [5]
 (If the shareholders all vote no, his candidates can lose, but with 40.4% =
of the vote that=E2=80=99s pretty unlikely.)=09His directors also get to se=
rve on all of the board=E2=80=99s committees.=09Ken Moelis has to give his =
prior approval for=C2=A0a bunch of specified corporate actions, including i=
ncurring debt, issuing stock, paying dividends, entering new lines of busin=
ess, adopting annual budgets and business plans, bringing lawsuits, signing=
 material contracts, removing or appointing executives and changing the com=
pany=E2=80=99s name.

A shareholder sued, arguing that this is not allowed: Moelis & Co. is a pub=
lic company incorporated in Delaware, which means that its board of directo=
rs has to be in charge of things like hiring and firing the CEO, entering n=
ew lines of business or changing its name. A contract can=E2=80=99t give it=
s founder the right to make those decisions=C2=A0instead of the board.
And last week a judge =E2=80=94=C2=A0Vice Chancellor Travis Laster of the D=
elaware Court of Chancery =E2=80=94=C2=A0agreed.  Here is his opinion, whic=
h finds that the requirement for Ken Moelis=E2=80=99s prior approval of cor=
porate actions is invalid:
Taken together, the Pre-Approval Requirements=C2=A0 force the Board to obta=
in Moelis=E2=80=99 prior written consent before taking virtually any meanin=
gful action. With the Pre-Approval Requirements in place, the Board is not =
really a board. The directors only manage the Company to the extent Moelis =
gives them permission to do so.=C2=A0
As are most of his rights to name directors: =E2=80=9CThe Recommendation Re=
quirement improperly compels the Board to recommend Moelis=E2=80=99designee=
s for election,=E2=80=9D even if the board doesn=E2=80=99t think those desi=
gnees are good, and =E2=80=9CDetermining the composition of committees fall=
s within the Board=E2=80=99s authority. A stockholder cannot determine who =
comprises a committee.=E2=80=9D
Now, at some level, none of this matters. As a 40% shareholder (by voting r=
ights), and the founder, CEO, chairman of the board and namesake of the fir=
m,=C2=A0Ken Moelis probably=C2=A0can=C2=A0get the board to do most of what =
he wants, with or without a contract. For one thing, the directors are prob=
ably there =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the board of the company he founded and contro=
ls =E2=80=94=C2=A0because they think his ideas are mostly good! But also he=
 has a lot of practical control. Moelis & Co. is not going to enter into an=
y new contracts or=C2=A0lines of business without his approval: He=E2=80=99=
s the CEO, he signs the contracts and picks the lines of business. And it=
=E2=80=99s not going to set up any board committees without his approval: H=
e=E2=80=99s the chairman of the board, he=E2=80=99s in the board meetings, =
and if the rest of the board votes to set up a committee without him, he do=
es =E2=80=94=C2=A0as the controlling-ish shareholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0probabl=
y have the power to vote them out. As long as he gets to nominate directors=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if the board decides not to recommend them =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0they=E2=80=99ll probably get elected, because he has 40% of the vote.
Also, even as a technical matter, there are ways around last week=E2=80=99s=
 decision. Vice Chancellor Laster writes:
Moelis did not have to frame an internal corporate governance arrangement u=
sing the Stockholder Agreement. He could have accomplished the vast majorit=
y of what he wanted through the Company=E2=80=99s certificate of incorporat=
ion (the =E2=80=9CCharter=E2=80=9D).=C2=A0Even now, the Board could impleme=
nt many of the Challenged Provisions by using its blank check authority to =
issue Moelis preferred stock carrying a set of voting rights and director a=
ppointment rights. A new class of preferred stock need not upset the Compan=
y=E2=80=99s equity allocation; it could consist of a single golden share. T=
he certificate of designations for the new preferred stock would become par=
t of the Charter as a matter of law.=C2=A0At that point, because the provis=
ions would appear in the Charter, they would comply with Section 141(a).
  [6]
 Although some might find it bizarre that the [Delaware General Corporation=
 Law] would prohibit one means of accomplishing a goal while allowing anoth=
er, that is what the doctrine of independent legal significance contemplate=
s.
A company=E2=80=99s charter can give a shareholder a lot of control over it=
s board and business, but an outside agreement can=E2=80=99t.
  [7]

Still, this decision will have some effects. As Vice Chancellor Laster writ=
es, there are a lot of agreements like this:
Corporate planners now regularly implement internal governance arrangements=
 through stockholder agreements. The new wave of stockholder agreements doe=
s not involve stockholders contracting among themselves to address how they=
 will exercise their stockholder-level rights. The new-wave agreements cont=
ain extensive veto rights and other restrictions on corporate action.
And now maybe they are all invalid?
In related news,   Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Jef Feeley and Crystal Tse report:

Crown Castle Inc. co-founder Ted Miller ratcheted up a proxy fight with the=
 cellular tower company=E2=80=99s board, suing directors over a cooperation=
 agreement they struck with Paul Singer=E2=80=99s Elliott Investment Manage=
ment.
Miller, who helped launch Crown Castle in 1994, says the board is improperl=
y beholden to activist investor Elliott, one of the company=E2=80=99s large=
st shareholders. Elliott signed a cooperation agreement with Crown Castle i=
n December and got two board seats.
The agreement amounts to an =E2=80=9Cunreasonable and disproportionate defe=
nsive measure,=E2=80=9D Miller argues in the suit, filed Tuesday in Delawar=
e Chancery Court. He is asking the court to invalidate the pact, which he s=
ays harms Crown Castle shareholders by subjecting them to =E2=80=9Cthe whim=
s of Elliott and the artificial constraints imposed=E2=80=9D by the pact on=
 decisions such as finding a new chief executive officer.
=E2=80=9CThe affairs of Delaware corporations, however, must be managed by =
boards of directors, not backroom deals,=E2=80=9D Miller said in the compla=
int.

Here is  the complaint. What happened here is that Crown Castle is a public=
 company that has had a rough run in recent years, and it attracted=C2=A0tw=
o=C2=A0activists: Elliott, a classic activist hedge fund that bought about =
$2 billion worth of Crown Castle stock, and Miller, the company=E2=80=99s f=
ounder, who was CEO from 1994 until 2002 and who still owns about $86 milli=
on worth of stock. Elliott threatened a proxy contest to get its own nomine=
es on the board of directors, and Crown Castle  quickly settled last Decemb=
er, agreeing to appoint two Elliott nominees to its board of directors. Ell=
iott and Crown Castle  signed a cooperation agreement in which they agreed =
on some plans, including forming a =E2=80=9Cfiber review committee=E2=80=9D=
 to think about what to do with its fiber business, forming a CEO search co=
mmittee to find a new CEO, and agreeing to support each other=E2=80=99s boa=
rd nominees. In particular, Crown Castle agreed that, at its 2024 annual me=
eting, =E2=80=9Cthe Company will recommend that the Company=E2=80=99s share=
holders vote in favor of the election of each of the Board=E2=80=99s nomine=
es,=E2=80=9D including the two Elliott representatives.
But Miller wants his say too, and he sued, claiming that this agreement giv=
es Elliott power improperly:

In sum, the Board had struck a grand bargain with Elliott: Elliott would ge=
t significant influence over the Company=E2=80=99s future direction and str=
ategy =E2=80=94 including seats at the table in selecting the next CEO and =
charting the Company=E2=80=99s course on Fiber strategy; in turn, Elliott w=
ould lay down its arms, and the incumbent directors would keep their jobs.
Neither the Company nor Elliott explained why ceding control over key gover=
nance decisions to Elliott, a single minority stockholder, while effectivel=
y entrenching the incumbent Board, would benefit stockholders.

And in particular, the agreement requires Crown Castle to recommend the Ell=
iott nominees to the board,=C2=A0even if it gets other, better nominees:
In their haste to lock in a deal and establish a frozen board, the Board ag=
reed to the Cooperation Agreement a month before the nomination window for =
the 2024 Annual Meeting opened and before it had an opportunity to hear tim=
ely alternative proposals from any other stockholders. The Director Defenda=
nts had a duty to consider stockholder proposals made during the nomination=
 window, which ran from January 18 to February 17, 2024, and to consider ea=
ch proposal on its merits. The Defendant Directors breached their contractu=
al obligations to stockholders by entering into the preclusive Cooperation =
Agreement foreclosing such consideration a month before the window opened.
At some level it seems obvious that the board of directors of a company fac=
ing a proxy fight might settle with the activist by signing a contract sayi=
ng =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll recommend two of your nominees to the board if yo=
u support the rest of ours.=E2=80=9D But is the board=C2=A0allowed=C2=A0to =
do that? Is it allowed to commit to making a governance decision like that,=
 without considering other possible nominees? Or does that violate the boar=
d=E2=80=99s obligation to run the company using its own best judgment?

