I sometimes write =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fraud=E2=80=9D as a sho=
rthand for a   particular weird argument about how modern US legal dynamics=
 transmute every bad action taken by a public company into securities fraud=
, but never mind that. A simpler story is that if the board of directors of=
 a company (public or private) puts out a public statement saying =E2=80=9C=
turns out our chief executive officer is a big liar,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0somebody=
=C2=A0is going to think that=E2=80=99s securities fraud. Whatever the CEO w=
as lying about was=C2=A0probably=C2=A0material to the company =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0otherwise why would the board care? =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you=E2=80=99ve go=
t to at least look into it.
This isn=E2=80=99t quite that, but=C2=A0the Wall Street Journal reports:

The Securities and Exchange Commission is scrutinizing internal communicati=
