The regulator, whose probe hasn=E2=80=99t previously been reported, has bee=
n seeking internal records from current and former OpenAI officials and dir=
ectors, and sent a subpoena to OpenAI in December, according to people fami=
liar with the matter. That followed the OpenAI board=E2=80=99s decision in =
November to fire Altman as CEO and oust him from the board. At the time, di=
rectors said Altman hadn=E2=80=99t been =E2=80=9Cconsistently candid in his=
 communications,=E2=80=9D but didn=E2=80=99t elaborate. =E2=80=A6
Some of the people familiar with the investigation described it as a predic=
table response to the former OpenAI board=E2=80=99s claim in its November s=
tatement. One of the people said that the SEC hasn=E2=80=99t pointed to any=
 specific statement or communication by Altman that it has deemed misleadin=
g.

Right, maybe they=E2=80=99ll find a =E2=80=9Cspecific statement or communic=
ation=E2=80=9D=C2=A0to investors=C2=A0that was misleading, and he=E2=80=99l=
l get in trouble; probably they won=E2=80=99t.
  [8]
 But if the board of directors of a giant company fires the CEO for the sta=
ted reason that he was=C2=A0not candid, the SEC really does have to look in=
to it.
=E2=80=9CA giant company,=E2=80=9D I said; not necessarily a public=C2=A0on=
e. =E2=80=9CThe SEC enforces laws that forbid people from misleading invest=
ors, regardless of whether fundraisers seek capital in public or private ma=
rkets,=E2=80=9D notes the Journal, correctly. Still there are some relevant=
 differences between OpenAI and most companies:
=09OpenAI=E2=80=99s stock does not continuously trade in public markets, so=
 its CEO could go around lying about lots of stuff without=C2=A0tricking in=
vestors into buying stock. If you are the CEO of a public company and you g=
o on television and say =E2=80=9Cwe have built a superintelligent robot tha=
t can cure cancer,=E2=80=9D people will buy your stock, the stock will go u=
p, and if it turns out you were lying, they will sue you for fraud. If you =
are the CEO of a private company and you do that, nobody will trade the sto=
ck, because they can=E2=80=99t. If you then try to raise money by selling s=
tock to investors two weeks later, and you send them a private placement me=
mo saying =E2=80=9Cwe have not built a superintelligent robot, we=E2=80=99r=
e not even working on cancer, our CEO was just letting off steam on TV,=E2=
=80=9D and then they buy the stock, they weren=E2=80=99t misled, were they?=
 This is very much not legal advice, don=E2=80=99t do it, but the point is =
that=C2=A0every public statement=C2=A0by a public-company CEO is risky, whi=
le private companies have more limited investment-related communications.=
=09In a typical=C2=A0private=C2=A0company, and particularly in a typical=C2=
=A0tech startup, if the CEO is lying to the board of directors, he is also =
lying to his investors, because ordinarily the board will include several r=
epresentatives of the venture capital firms that invest in the business. So=
 if the board feels misled, the investors probably feel misled, because the=
y=E2=80=99re the same people. That's not the case here. In fact, it is exac=
tly the opposite here: OpenAI=E2=80=99s =09description of its corporate str=
ucture says =E2=80=9Cthe board remains majority independent,=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cindependent directors do not hold equity in OpenAI.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0=
(Microsoft Corp., OpenAI=E2=80=99s biggest investor, is represented by=C2=
=A0an observer on the board, but has no voting rights, and even the observe=
r seat came after Altman=E2=80=99s firing and unfiring.) So in some sense t=
he board of directors was a good group for Altman to mislead: They weren=E2=
=80=99t investors!=09I continue to find it funny and relevant that, at the =
top of  OpenAI=E2=80=99s operating agreement, it warns investors: =E2=80=9C=
It would be wise to view any investment in OpenAI Global, LLC in the spirit=
 of a donation, with the understanding that it may be difficult to know wha=
t role money will play in a post-[artificial general intelligence] world.=
=E2=80=9D I still don=E2=80=99t know what Altman was supposedly not candid =
