On the other hand, the general idea of =E2=80=9Ceverything is securities fr=
aud=E2=80=9D is that if investors care about a thing, and the company says =
misleading stuff about the thing, then that=E2=80=99s securities fraud.=C2=
=A0Traditionally, investors cared about things like profits, and companies =
sometimes cooked their books to show misleading profit numbers, and that wa=
s traditional securities=C2=A0fraud. But the modern theory understands that=
 investors care about lots of things that could impact the company=E2=80=99=
s business =E2=80=94=C2=A0its policies for   securing customer data, its   =
treatment of its employees, its  treatment of its whales =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 misleading investors about any of those things could be fraud.
In the modern world of environmental, social and governance (ESG) investing=
, it seems pretty uncontroversial to say that at least=C2=A0some investors =
care about a company=E2=80=99s environmental record. And thus lying about y=
our environmental record gives investors =E2=80=94=C2=A0or regulators =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a securities-fraud hook to sue you.
You could imagine some sort of world in which governments directly regulate=
d companies=E2=80=99 environmental behavior, in which people made collectiv=
e judgments about climate trade-offs through a democratic process, governme=
nts made rules enacting those judgments, companies followed those rules, an=
d people got the level of emissions that they wanted. It=E2=80=99s one appr=
oach.
But I think that the US approach is, roughly, that people make rough collec=
tive judgments about climate trade-offs=C2=A0through their ownership of ESG=
 investment vehicles, investment managers pressure companies to enact those=
 judgments, companies respond to those pressures by making environmental pr=
omises, and US regulators   regulate those promises and punish the companie=
s when they are false. Environmental regulation through securities fraud. I=
t does seem second-best? Bloomberg News reports:

New York state is suing JBS SA over allegations the world=E2=80=99s biggest=
 meat-packer misled =E2=80=9Cthe public about its environmental impact.=E2=
=80=9D
New York Attorney General Letitia James said the meat producer has failed t=
o provide a viable plan to meet a widely-advertised commitment to reach net=
 zero emissions by 2040 and that it could not feasibly meet such a goal, ac=
cording to a filing. The company =E2=80=9Chas made several misleading claim=
s about its environmental impact, including pledges to curb deforestation a=
nd reduce its greenhouse gas emissions,=E2=80=9D a statement from the attor=
ney general=E2=80=99s office said.
Several companies across different industries have made net zero commitment=
s over the past few years amid growing pressure from investors, regulators =
and environmental groups. Still, many of them are yet to provide a clear pa=
thway for decarbonization. Climate-washing claims against business have als=
o become more usual, with most cases being originated in the US.

Right. I will say it is kind of strange to sue a company specifically=C2=A0=
for lying about whether it will have net zero emissions by 2040. It=E2=80=
=99s only 2024! How can you prove that?

