ent Inc.=E2=80=99s directors pushed out Vince McMahon, WWE=E2=80=99s majori=
ty owner, and then he fired them in return.


  [3] At least for Delaware public companies. I think people at least impli=
citly accept a bit more informality for private startups.


  [4] See pages 23 and 24 of last week=E2=80=99s opinion, or the 2023 proxy=
 statement.


  [5] The agreement was written when he had a majority of the voting power,=
 and he keeps this right even with a minority of the votes (though if he se=
lls down enough stock he will eventually lose it). But the opinion notes th=
at =E2=80=9CMoelis is still entitled to designate a majority of the Board, =
but he waived that right in 2021, 2022, and 2023 to ensure compliance with =
the [New York Stock Exchange] rules for non-controlled companies.=E2=80=9D


  [6] Section 141(a) of the Delaware General Corporation Law is the provisi=
on saying that =E2=80=9CThe business and affairs of every corporation organ=
ized under this chapter shall be managed by or under the direction of a boa=
rd of directors, except as may be otherwise provided in this chapter or in =
its certificate of incorporation.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=9CSection 141(a) is the s=
ource of Delaware=E2=80=99s board-centric model of corporate governance,=E2=
=80=9D writes Vice Chancellor Laster.=E2=80=9D


  [7] Actually there is a complication there: Some contracts obviously can =
give outsiders control over a company=E2=80=99s business decisions. For ins=
tance, it is common for a credit agreement =E2=80=94 a contract between the=
 company and its lenders =E2=80=94 to limit the company=E2=80=99s ability t=
o incur new debt, just like the Moelis & Co. stockholder agreement does. Vi=
ce Chancellor Laster writes: =E2=80=9CDelaware corporations possess the pow=
er to contract, and contracts necessarily constrain a board=E2=80=99s freed=
om of action. A corporation that has agreed to an exclusive supply contract=
 cannot freely contract with a different supplier. No one would suggest tha=
t an exclusive supply contract violates Section 141(a). Not only that, but =
Delaware corporations can enter into commercial contracts that constrain sp=
ecific acts otherwise entrusted to the board. Under a credit agreement, for=
 example, declaring a dividend or buying back stock can be events of defaul=
t. Both are board level decisions, so those provisions limit the board=E2=
=80=99s freedom of action. Yet both are legitimate protections for a lender=
 to demand.=E2=80=9D But he concludes that there=E2=80=99s a difference bet=
ween a =E2=80=9Ccommercial contract=E2=80=9D and an =E2=80=9Cinternal gover=
nance arrangement,=E2=80=9D and that boards of directors can give up some f=
reedom as part of a commercial contract but not just as part of this stockh=
older agreement.


  [8] Famously, after briefly firing Altman,   the old board told employees=
 =E2=80=9Cthat Altman wasn=E2=80=99t candid, and often got his way,=E2=80=
=9D but also =E2=80=9Cthat Altman had been so deft they couldn=E2=80=99t ev=
en give a specific example."


