adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Moelis, Crown Castle</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic rule is that the board of directors =
of a company is in charge of the company, and when they are faced with a de=
cision, the directors are supposed to make the choice that they believe is =
best for the company and all of its shareholders. The shareholders don=E2=
=80=99t make the decision; the board does.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=
=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inli=
ne-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, the directors are elected by the sharehol=
ders, and when the company has a controlling shareholder, the idea that the=
 directors are in charge can feel somewhat absurd. The controlling sharehol=
der =E2=80=94=C2=A0say, a founder and chief executive officer who owns 60% =
of the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0can come into the boardroom and say =E2=80=9CI =
want you to sell all of the company=E2=80=99s assets to me for $1,=E2=80=9D=
 and the directors will say =E2=80=9Cno, in our independent judgment that=
=E2=80=99s a bad idea,=E2=80=9D and the founder/CEO/shareholder will say =
=E2=80=9Cokay you=E2=80=99re fired,=E2=80=9D and she will replace them with=
 more pliable directors. And she can do that, because she has the votes.<a =
class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text=
-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color=
: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpar=
ent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But still: The directors are supposed to exercise their independe=
nt judgment and do what is in the company=E2=80=99s best interests, and if =
they conclude that the founder/CEO=E2=80=99s plan is bad, they have to say =
no and get fired. They can=E2=80=99t just say =E2=80=9Cwell, ultimately she=
 controls the company, so we have to do what she asks.=E2=80=9D Exercising =
independent judgment is their job.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I cannot promise that every board of directors=
 of every company sees things this way =E2=80=94=C2=A0I think some director=
s of private startups see their job as =E2=80=9Cadvise and empower the foun=
der/CEO=E2=80=9D rather than =E2=80=9Cexercise independent judgment=E2=80=
=9D =E2=80=94=C2=A0but the courts in Delaware, where most US public compani=
es are incorporated, definitely see things this way.<a class=3D"footnote-in=
dex" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; disp=
lay: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So we <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34=
519830.285376/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwM=
jQtMDEtMzEvZWxvbi1tdXNrLWlzLW92ZXJwYWlkP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjkyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZG=
JnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIyOSZ=
1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf8409af8" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
  talked recently</a>=C2=A0about a Delaware court decision overturning Elon=
 Musk=E2=80=99s pay package at Tesla Inc. The basic theory there was that M=
usk is Tesla=E2=80=99s controlling shareholder (even though he owns a minor=
ity of the stock), and that the board did not exercise sufficient independe=
nt judgment in deciding what to pay him: He asked for a pay package and the=
y deferred to what he wanted. Not okay, said the judge; the board has a dut=
y to make its own independent determination of what he should be paid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ken Moelis is the founder, chief executive off=
icer and chairman of the board of directors of Moelis &amp; Co., the invest=
ment bank. In 2014, Moelis &amp; Co. went public, and over time Ken Moelis =
sold some of his stock. He now owns about 6.5% of the stock, but he has som=
e supervoting shares, which give him about 40.4% of the voting power of the=
 stock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color: #00=
0000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bo=
ttom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color=
: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0That=E2=80=99s not a majority, but it=E2=80=99s a lot more than E=
lon Musk owns of Tesla:=C2=A0Ken Moelis is not necessarily the controlling =
shareholder of Moelis &amp; Co., but he=E2=80=99s at least pretty close.</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beyond his voting stake, though, Ken Moelis ha=
s some extra control over his company. Specifically there is a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34519830.285376/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3=
cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE1OTY5NjcvMDAwMTEwNDY1OTE0MDI5MjE1L=
2ExNC0xMDkxMl8xZXgxMGQxLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB17f9f5e9" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 Stockholders Agreement</a>=C2=A0that gives Ken Moelis some rights to contr=
ol the company:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">He gets to designate a majority of th=
e board of directors: He can name his candidates, and the company=E2=80=99s=
 board is obligated to nominate them, recommend that stockholders vote for =
them, and try to get them elected.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-5" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[5]</span>
</a> (If the shareholders all vote no, his candidates can lose, but with 40=
.4% of the vote that=E2=80=99s pretty unlikely.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">His directors also get to serve on all of the board=E2=80=99=
s committees.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Ken Moelis has to gi=
ve his prior approval for=C2=A0a bunch of specified corporate actions, incl=
uding incurring debt, issuing stock, paying dividends, entering new lines o=
f business, adopting annual budgets and business plans, bringing lawsuits, =
signing material contracts, removing or appointing executives and changing =
the company=E2=80=99s name.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A shareholder sued, arguing that this is not a=
llowed: Moelis &amp; Co. is a public company incorporated in Delaware, whic=
h means that its <em>board of directors</em> has to be in charge of things =
like hiring and firing the CEO, entering new lines of business or changing =
its name. A contract can=E2=80=99t give its founder the right to make those=
 decisions=C2=A0instead of the board.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And last week a judge =E2=80=94=C2=A0Vice Chan=
cellor Travis Laster of the Delaware Court of Chancery =E2=80=94=C2=A0agree=
d. <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34519830.285376=
/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9Mz=
YwNDYw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB0dbdce73" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Here is his opinion</a>=
, which finds that the requirement for Ken Moelis=E2=80=99s prior approval =
of corporate actions is invalid:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Taken together, the Pre-Approval R=
equirements=C2=A0 force the Board to obtain Moelis=E2=80=99 prior written c=
onsent before taking virtually any meaningful action. With the Pre-Approval=
 Requirements in place, the Board is not really a board. The directors only=
 manage the Company to the extent Moelis gives them permission to do so.=C2=
=A0</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As are most of his rights to name directors: =
=E2=80=9CThe Recommendation Requirement improperly compels the Board to rec=
ommend Moelis=E2=80=99<br />designees for election,=E2=80=9D even if the bo=
ard doesn=E2=80=99t think those designees are good, and =E2=80=9CDeterminin=
g the composition of committees falls within the Board=E2=80=99s authority.=
 A stockholder cannot determine who comprises a committee.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, at some level, none of this matters. As a=
 40% shareholder (by voting rights), and the founder, CEO, chairman of the =
board and namesake of the firm,=C2=A0Ken Moelis probably=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0=
</em>get the board to do most of what he wants, with or without a contract.=
 For one thing, the directors are probably there =E2=80=94=C2=A0on the boar=
d of the company he founded and controls =E2=80=94=C2=A0because they think =
his ideas are mostly good! But also he has a lot of practical control. Moel=
is &amp; Co. is not going to enter into any new contracts or=C2=A0lines of =
business without his approval: He=E2=80=99s the CEO, he signs the contracts=
 and picks the lines of business. And it=E2=80=99s not going to set up any =
board committees without his approval: He=E2=80=99s the chairman of the boa=
rd, he=E2=80=99s in the board meetings, and if the rest of the board votes =
to set up a committee without him, he does =E2=80=94=C2=A0as the controllin=
g-ish shareholder =E2=80=94=C2=A0probably have the power to vote them out. =
As long as he gets to nominate directors =E2=80=94=C2=A0even if the board d=
ecides not to recommend them =E2=80=94=C2=A0they=E2=80=99ll probably get el=
ected, because he has 40% of the vote.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, even as a technical matter, there are wa=
ys around last week=E2=80=99s decision. Vice Chancellor Laster writes:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Moelis did not have to frame an in=
ternal corporate governance arrangement using the Stockholder Agreement. He=
 could have accomplished the vast majority of what he wanted through the Co=
mpany=E2=80=99s certificate of incorporation (the =E2=80=9CCharter=E2=80=9D=
).=C2=A0Even now, the Board could implement many of the Challenged Provisio=
ns by using its blank check authority to issue Moelis preferred stock carry=
ing a set of voting rights and director appointment rights. A new class of =
preferred stock need not upset the Company=E2=80=99s equity allocation; it =
could consist of a single golden share. The certificate of designations for=
 the new preferred stock would become part of the Charter as a matter of la=
w.=C2=A0At that point, because the provisions would appear in the Charter, =
they would comply with Section 141(a).<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#=
footnote-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: no=
ne !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-bl=
ock;">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> Although some might find it bizarre that the [Delaware General Corpora=
tion Law] would prohibit one means of accomplishing a goal while allowing a=
nother, that is what the doctrine of independent legal significance contemp=
lates.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A company=E2=80=99s charter can give a shareho=
lder a lot of control over its board and business, but an outside agreement=
 can=E2=80=99t.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-7" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgrou=
nd-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[7]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, this decision will have some effects. A=
s Vice Chancellor Laster writes, there are a lot of agreements like this:</=
p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Corporate planners now regularly i=
mplement internal governance arrangements through stockholder agreements. T=
he new wave of stockholder agreements does not involve stockholders contrac=
ting among themselves to address how they will exercise their stockholder-l=
evel rights. The new-wave agreements contain extensive veto rights and othe=
r restrictions on corporate action.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And now maybe they are all invalid?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In related news, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.=
bloombergbusiness.com/click/34519830.285376/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmN=
vbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjgvY3Jvd24tY2FzdGxlLWRpcmVjdG9ycy1zdWVkLW=
J5LWNvLWZvdW5kZXItb3Zlci1lbGxpb3R0LXBhY3Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyOTI0X01PTkVZU1RVR=
kYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjI5=
JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBb2a17596" itempro=
p=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #=
000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-=
bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"=
>  Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Jef Feeley and Crystal Tse report</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Crown Castle Inc. co-founder Ted Miller ratche=
ted up a proxy fight with the cellular tower company=E2=80=99s board, suing=
 directors over a cooperation agreement they struck with Paul Singer=E2=80=
=99s Elliott Investment Management.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Miller, who helped launch Crown Castle in 1994=
, says the board is improperly beholden to activist investor Elliott, one o=
f the company=E2=80=99s largest shareholders. Elliott signed a cooperation =
agreement with Crown Castle in December and got two board seats.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The agreement amounts to an =E2=80=9Cunreasona=
ble and disproportionate defensive measure,=E2=80=9D Miller argues in the s=
uit, filed Tuesday in Delaware Chancery Court. He is asking the court to in=
validate the pact, which he says harms Crown Castle shareholders by subject=
ing them to =E2=80=9Cthe whims of Elliott and the artificial constraints im=
posed=E2=80=9D by the pact on decisions such as finding a new chief executi=
ve officer.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe affairs of Delaware corporations,=
 however, must be managed by boards of directors, not backroom deals,=E2=80=
=9D Miller said in the complaint.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/34519830.285376/aHR0cHM6Ly9hc3NldHMuYndieC5pby9kb2N1bWVu=
dHMvdXNlcnMvaXFqV0hCRmRmeElVL3JQY3d5Q2JvaFhQcy92MA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bba7f13ca" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;"> the complaint</a>. What happened here is that Crown Cas=
tle is a public company that has had a rough run in recent years, and it at=
tracted=C2=A0<em>two=C2=A0</em>activists: Elliott, a classic activist hedge=
 fund that bought about $2 billion worth of Crown Castle stock, and Miller,=
 the company=E2=80=99s founder, who was CEO from 1994 until 2002 and who st=
ill owns about $86 million worth of stock. Elliott threatened a proxy conte=
st to get its own nominees on the board of directors, and Crown Castle <a h=
ref=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34519830.285376/aHR0cH=
M6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9peHZpZXdlci9peC5odG1sP2RvYz0vQXJjaGl2ZXMvZWRnYXIvZGF0Y=
S8xMDUxNDcwLzAwMDExOTMxMjUyMzI5OTQwMi9kNzYxODI1ZDhrLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cBad3bb014" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> quickly settled last December</a>, agreeing to a=
ppoint two Elliott nominees to its board of directors. Elliott and Crown Ca=
stle <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34519830.2853=
76/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzEwNTE0NzAvMDAwMTE5=
MzEyNTIzMjk5NDAyL2Q3NjE4MjVkZXgxMDEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1734d5f7"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;"> signed a cooperation agreement</a> in which they agreed on some p=
lans, including forming a =E2=80=9Cfiber review committee=E2=80=9D to think=
 about what to do with its fiber business, forming a CEO search committee t=
o find a new CEO, and agreeing to support each other=E2=80=99s board nomine=
es. In particular, Crown Castle agreed that, at its 2024 annual meeting, =
=E2=80=9Cthe Company will recommend that the Company=E2=80=99s shareholders=
 vote in favor of the election of each of the Board=E2=80=99s nominees,=E2=
=80=9D including the two Elliott representatives.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But Miller wants his say too, and he sued, cla=
iming that this agreement gives Elliott power improperly:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In sum, the Board had struck a grand bargain w=
ith Elliott: Elliott would get significant influence over the Company=E2=80=
=99s future direction and strategy =E2=80=94 including seats at the table i=
n selecting the next CEO and charting the Company=E2=80=99s course on Fiber=
 strategy; in turn, Elliott would lay down its arms, and the incumbent dire=
ctors would keep their jobs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Neither the Company nor Elliott explained why =
ceding control over key governance decisions to Elliott, a single minority =
stockholder, while effectively entrenching the incumbent Board, would benef=
it stockholders.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in particular, the agreement requires Crow=
n Castle to recommend the Elliott nominees to the board,=C2=A0<em>even if i=
t gets other, better nominees:</em></p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In their haste to lock in a deal a=
nd establish a frozen board, the Board agreed to the Cooperation Agreement =
a month before the nomination window for the 2024 Annual Meeting opened and=
 before it had an opportunity to hear timely alternative proposals from any=
 other stockholders. The Director Defendants had a duty to consider stockho=
lder proposals made during the nomination window, which ran from January 18=
 to February 17, 2024, and to consider each proposal on its merits. The Def=
endant Directors breached their contractual obligations to stockholders by =
entering into the preclusive Cooperation Agreement foreclosing such conside=
ration a month before the window opened.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At some level it seems obvious that the board =
of directors of a company facing a proxy fight might settle with the activi=
st by signing a contract saying =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll recommend two of you=
r nominees to the board if you support the rest of ours.=E2=80=9D But is th=
e board=C2=A0<em>allowed=C2=A0</em>to do that? Is it allowed to commit to m=
aking a governance decision like that, without considering other possible n=
ominees? Or does that violate the board=E2=80=99s obligation to run the com=
pany using its own best judgment?</p>
