<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the modern world of environmental, social a=
nd governance (ESG) investing, it seems pretty uncontroversial to say that =
at least=C2=A0<em>some </em>investors care about a company=E2=80=99s enviro=
nmental record. And thus lying about your environmental record gives invest=
ors =E2=80=94=C2=A0or regulators =E2=80=94=C2=A0a securities-fraud hook to =
sue you.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You could imagine some sort of world in which =
governments directly regulated companies=E2=80=99 environmental behavior, i=
n which people made collective judgments about climate trade-offs through a=
 democratic process, governments made rules enacting those judgments, compa=
nies followed those rules, and people got the level of emissions that they =
wanted. It=E2=80=99s one approach.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I think that the US approach is, roughly, =
that people make rough collective judgments about climate trade-offs=C2=A0<=
em>through their ownership of ESG investment vehicles</em>, investment mana=
